20 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
21 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
22 Article – Insurance
23 15–830.
24 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
25 (2) “Carrier” means:
26 (i) an insurer that offers health insurance other than long–term
27 care insurance or disability insurance;
28 (ii) a nonprofit health service plan;
29 (iii) a health maintenance organization;
30 (iv) a dental plan organization; or
31 (v) except for a managed care organization as defined in Title 15,
32 Subtitle 1 of the Health – General Article, any other person that provides health benefit
33 plans subject to State regulation.

SENATE BILL 891 3
1 (3) (i) “Member” means an individual entitled to health care benefits
2 under a policy or plan issued or delivered in the State by a carrier.
3 (ii) “Member” includes a subscriber.
4 (4) “MENTAL HEALTH DISORDER” INCLUDES A PERINATAL MENTAL
5 HEALTH CONDITION.
6 [(4)] (5) “Nonphysician specialist” means a health care provider:
7 (i) 1. who is not a physician;
8 2. who is licensed or certified under the Health Occupations
9 Article; and
10 3. who is certified or trained to treat or provide health care
11 services for a specified condition or disease in a manner that is within the scope of the
12 license or certification of the health care provider; or
13 (ii) that is licensed as a behavioral health program under § 7.5–401
14 of the Health – General Article.
15 (6) (I) “PERINATAL MENTAL HEALTH CONDITION” MEANS A
16 MENTAL HEALTH CONDITION OCCURRING DURING PREGNANCY, THE POSTPARTUM
17 PERIOD, OR THE PERINATAL PERIOD.
18 (II) “PERINATAL MENTAL HEALTH CONDITION” INCLUDES
19 POSTPARTUM DEPRESSION.
20 [(5)] (7) (i) “Provider panel” means the providers that contract with a
21 carrier either directly or through a subcontracting entity to provide health care services to
22 enrollees of the carrier.
23 (ii) “Provider panel” does not include an arrangement in which any
24 provider may participate solely by contracting with the carrier to provide health care
25 services at a discounted fee–for–service rate.
26 [(6)] (8) “Specialist” means a physician who is certified or trained to
27 practice in a specified field of medicine and who is not designated as a primary care provider
28 by the carrier.
29 (c) (1) (I) Notwithstanding any other provision of this section, a member
30 who is pregnant shall receive a standing referral to an obstetrician, in accordance with this
31 subsection.

4 SENATE BILL 891
1 [(2)] (II) After the member who is pregnant receives a standing referral to
2 an obstetrician, the obstetrician is responsible for the primary management of the
3 member’s pregnancy, including the issuance of referrals in accordance with the carrier’s
4 policies and procedures, through the postpartum period.
5 (2) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER PROVISION OF THIS SECTION, A
6 MEMBER SHALL RECEIVE A STANDING REFERRAL TO A MENTAL HEALTH CARE
7 PROVIDER, IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SUBSECTION, FOR THE DURATION OF THE
8 MEMBER’S PREGNANCY AND 1 YEAR AFTER THE MEMBER GIVES BIRTH.
9 (3) A written treatment plan may not be required when a standing referral
10 is to an obstetrician OR MENTAL HEALTH CARE PROVIDER under this subsection.
11 (d) (1) Each carrier shall establish and implement a procedure by which a
12 member may request a referral to a specialist or nonphysician specialist who is not part of
13 the carrier’s provider panel in accordance with this subsection.
14 (2) The procedure shall provide for a referral to a specialist or nonphysician
15 specialist who is not part of the carrier’s provider panel if:
16 (i) 1. the member is diagnosed with a condition or disease that
17 requires specialized health care services or medical care; and
18 2. A. the carrier does not have in its provider panel a
19 specialist or nonphysician specialist with the professional training and expertise to treat or
20 provide health care services for the condition or disease; or
21 B. the carrier cannot provide reasonable access to a specialist
22 or nonphysician specialist with the professional training and expertise to treat or provide
23 health care services for the condition or disease without unreasonable delay or travel,
24 including within the reasonable appointment waiting time and travel distance standards
25 established in regulation for mental health and substance use disorder services; or
26 (ii) 1. the member is seeking mental health or substance use
27 disorder care; and
28 2. the carrier cannot provide reasonable access to a specialist
29 or nonphysician specialist within the reasonable appointment waiting time and travel
30 distance standards established in regulation for mental health and substance use disorder
31 services.
32 (3) The procedure shall ensure that a request to obtain a referral to a
33 specialist or nonphysician specialist who is not part of the carrier’s provider panel is
34 addressed in a timely manner that is:
35 (i) appropriate for the member’s condition; and

SENATE BILL 891 5
1 (ii) in accordance with the timeliness requirements for
2 determinations made by private review agents under § 15–10B–06 of this title.
3 (4) If a member cannot access mental health or substance use disorder
4 services through the referral requirements under paragraphs (2) and (3) of this subsection,
5 the procedure shall require the carrier to provide additional assistance to the member in
6 identifying and arranging coverage of mental health or substance use disorder services by
7 a specialist or nonphysician specialist who is not part of the carrier’s provider panel.
8 (5) If a carrier approves a member’s request for a referral made in
9 accordance with this subsection, the carrier may not require utilization review other than
10 what would be required if the covered benefit were provided by a provider on the carrier’s
11 provider panel.
12 (6) The procedure may not be used by a carrier as a substitute for
13 establishing and maintaining a sufficient provider network in accordance with § 15–112 of
14 this title.
15 (7) Each carrier shall:
16 (i) have a system in place that documents all requests to obtain a
17 referral to receive a covered service from a specialist or nonphysician specialist who is not
18 part of the carrier’s provider panel;
19 (ii) inform members of the procedure to request a referral under
20 paragraph (1) of this subsection; and
21 (iii) provide the information documented under item (i) of this
22 paragraph to the Commissioner on request.
23 15–864.
24 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “PERINATAL MENTAL HEALTH CONDITION” HAS THE
25 MEANING STATED IN § 15–830 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
26 (B) THIS SECTION APPLIES TO:
27 (1) INSURERS AND NONPROFIT HEALTH SERVICE PLANS THAT
28 PROVIDE HOSPITAL, MEDICAL, OR SURGICAL BENEFITS TO INDIVIDUALS OR GROUPS
29 ON AN EXPENSE–INCURRED BASIS UNDER HEALTH INSURANCE POLICIES OR
30 CONTRACTS THAT ARE ISSUED OR DELIVERED IN THE STATE; AND
31 (2) HEALTH MAINTENANCE ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROVIDE
32 HOSPITAL, MEDICAL, OR SURGICAL BENEFITS TO INDIVIDUALS OR GROUPS UNDER
33 CONTRACTS THAT ARE ISSUED OR DELIVERED IN THE STATE.

6 SENATE BILL 891
1 (C) (1) AN ENTITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION SHALL PROVIDE
2 COVERAGE FOR SCREENING FOR PERINATAL MENTAL HEALTH CONDITIONS:
3 (I) AT EACH PRENATAL VISIT;
4 (II) AT LEAST ONCE WITHIN 6 WEEKS AFTER THE INSURED OR
5 ENROLLEE GAVE BIRTH; AND
6 (III) AT EACH WELL CHILD VISIT WITHIN THE FIRST YEAR OF THE
7 CHILD’S LIFE.
8 (2) (I) SUBJECT TO SUBPARAGRAPH (II) OF THIS PARAGRAPH, AN
9 ENTITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION MAY SUBJECT THE COVERAGE REQUIRED UNDER
10 THIS SUBSECTION TO A COPAYMENT OR COINSURANCE REQUIREMENT OR
11 DEDUCTIBLE THAT AN ENTITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION IMPOSES FOR SIMILAR
12 COVERAGES UNDER THE SAME POLICY OR CONTRACT.
13 (II) THE COPAYMENT OR COINSURANCE REQUIREMENT OR
14 DEDUCTIBLE IMPOSED UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH MAY NOT BE
15 GREATER THAN THE COPAYMENT OR COINSURANCE REQUIREMENT OR DEDUCTIBLE
16 IMPOSED BY THE ENTITY FOR SIMILAR COVERAGES.
17 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
18 as follows:
19 Article – Health – General
20 20–1801.
21 (A) IN THIS SUBTITLE THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
22 INDICATED.
23 (B) “HEALTH CARE PROVIDER” MEANS A PERSON WHO IS LICENSED,
24 CERTIFIED, OR OTHERWISE AUTHORIZED UNDER THE HEALTH OCCUPATIONS
25 ARTICLE TO PROVIDE HEALTH OR MEDICAL CARE IN THE ORDINARY COURSE OF
26 BUSINESS OR PRACTICE OF A PROFESSION.
27 (C) (1) “PERINATAL MENTAL HEALTH CONDITION” MEANS A MENTAL
28 HEALTH CONDITION OCCURRING DURING PREGNANCY, THE POSTPARTUM PERIOD,
29 OR THE PERINATAL PERIOD.
30 (2) “PERINATAL MENTAL HEALTH CONDITION” INCLUDES
31 POSTPARTUM DEPRESSION.

